The general workflow of unit testing

Question about what’s the high-level takeaway on when/how-much to unit test:

  • Write your function to a point where you think “it works”
  • Write one unit test, starting from the “simplest and lowest-level” functions (typicall your helper functions), testing for just completion – does my function even complete for the simplest possible input?
  • Work your way up to writing a test of completion for your main function (the “main” function)

The general workflow of unit testing

Question about what’s the high-level takeaway on when/how-much to unit test:

  • Write your function to a point where you think “it works”
  • Write one unit test, starting from the “simplest and lowest-level” functions (typicall your helper functions), testing for just completion – does my function even complete for the simplest possible input?
  • Work your way up to writing a test of completion for your main function (the “main” function)
  • Often, some function’s output are the input of other functions. Hence, write tests starting from the “functions that are used first.”
  • Then, each function has one (very simple) unit test. Now, whenever possible, write one unit test for each function that demonstrates its “correctness”. This will be conceptually easier to do for some function than others. The more “self-evidently correct” a function is (i.e., it’s so simple that there’s no way there’s a bug), the less tests you need to write for that function.
  • Eventually, you’ll work up to write a test of correctness for your main function. (At this point, it might not be “strong certification” of correctness, but you should have some confidence that your function is probably doing something reasonable at this point. You’ve written some simple tests for completion and correctness for the main function and all the helper functions it depends on.)
  • During this process, write some unit tests that verify things that you’re really scared of happening. (As you get more experience in coding, you’ll know what will scare you.)

The general workflow of unit testing

Question about what’s the high-level takeaway on when/how-much to unit test:

  • Write your function to a point where you think “it works”
  • Write one unit test, starting from the “simplest and lowest-level” functions (typicall your helper functions), testing for just completion – does my function even complete for the simplest possible input?
  • Work your way up to writing a test of completion for your main function (the “main” function)
  • Often, some function’s output are the input of other functions. Hence, write tests starting from the “functions that are used first.”
  • Then, each function has one (very simple) unit test. Now, whenever possible, write one unit test for each function that demonstrates its “correctness”. This will be conceptually easier to do for some function than others. The more “self-evidently correct” a function is (i.e., it’s so simple that there’s no way there’s a bug), the less tests you need to write for that function.
  • Eventually, you’ll work up to write a test of correctness for your main function. (At this point, it might not be “strong certification” of correctness, but you should have some confidence that your function is probably doing something reasonable at this point. You’ve written some simple tests for completion and correctness for the main function and all the helper functions it depends on.)
  • During this process, write some unit tests that verify things that you’re really scared of happening. (As you get more experience in coding, you’ll know what will scare you.)
  • Now you’re ready to start using your code. As you use your code, you will find more bugs that you haven’t anticipated. This is normal. After you fix that bug, write unit tests for the relevant functions that were affected to make sure such a bug does not happen again.
  • As you use your code more and more, you will naturally write more and more unit tests. Hence, you don’t need to worry about “writing all the possible unit tests before using your function.” Ain’t no one got time for that. Once you have some (weak) evidence that your function “works,” get out there and start trying it out how you were originally intending to use it, and you’ll naturally find more and more bugs.
  • Each unit test should be a “minimal example.” That is, a unit test should not take more than a minute to complete.
  • Whenever you notice something strange in your code, write a unit test (i.e., a “minimal example” that also has this behavior) that exhibits this. This process will illuminate whether or not this was your intended behavior.
  • Creating a “minimal example” is a skill in itself. This forces you to think about how to generate simple inputs for each of your functions.

  • Remember: You will never find all the bugs in your code on your first pass. The bugs are always there, and the only question is when and how you’ll find them.

  • Never worry about if your unit test is “redundant.” You are never worried about having too many unit tests. You’re only worried about having too many.

  • As you start layering more and more unit tests, you’ll find bugs (sometimes in places you weren’t expecting).

  • In larger projects, the real workflow is that you test your teammates code, and your teammate tests your code. In my experience, I find it easier to write tests for someone else’s code since I’m naturally more skeptic on its correctness.

  • To install your R package, simply run devtools::install() in your R console.
  • Similar to running devtools::test() or devtools::test(), you need to make sure you’re in the R project for your R package.

Adding “verbose” statements in your functions

  • When you write a function with a big loop, you might often want to print out the progress of that function (so you know what’s going on)
  • The most common way I do this is to print out statements
  • The following function is to compute bootstrapped confidence intervals for linear regression coefficients
  • Notice we can put print statements inside the function
  • This statement only triggers when verbose > 0
bootstrap_lm <- function(X, y, 
                         alpha = 0.05,
                         nboot = 1000,
                         verbose = 0){
  n <- nrow(X)
  coef_mat <- matrix(NA, 
                     ncol = ncol(X) + 1,
                     nrow = nboot)
  
  if(verbose > 0) print("Starting bootstrap")
  for(i in 1:nboot){
    if(verbose > 0 && nboot > 10 && i %% floor(nboot/10) == 0) cat('*')
    idx <- sample(1:n, n, replace = TRUE)
    X2 <- X[idx,]
    y2 <- y[idx]
    lm_res <- stats::lm(y2 ~ X2)
    coef_mat[i,] <- stats::coef(lm_res)
  }
  
  if(verbose > 0) cat("\nComputing the CI\n")
  quantile_mat <- apply(coef_mat, 2, function(x){
    stats::quantile(x, probs = c(alpha/2, 1-alpha/2))
  })
  colnames(quantile_mat) <- c("(Intercept)", colnames(X))
  
  return(quantile_mat)
}
  • We can also print out stars as our function progresses
  • This is helpful since we can visually see what the progress is
  • These print statements only trigger if 1) there are more than 10 bootstrap trials (i.e., nboot > 10), and 2) we have completed an additional 1/10th of the bootstrap trials (i.e., i %% floor(nboot/10) == 0)
bootstrap_lm <- function(X, y, 
                         alpha = 0.05,
                         nboot = 1000,
                         verbose = 0){
  n <- nrow(X)
  coef_mat <- matrix(NA, 
                     ncol = ncol(X) + 1,
                     nrow = nboot)
  
  if(verbose > 0) print("Starting bootstrap")
  for(i in 1:nboot){
    if(verbose > 0 && nboot > 10 && i %% floor(nboot/10) == 0) cat('*')
    idx <- sample(1:n, n, replace = TRUE)
    X2 <- X[idx,]
    y2 <- y[idx]
    lm_res <- stats::lm(y2 ~ X2)
    coef_mat[i,] <- stats::coef(lm_res)
  }
  
  if(verbose > 0) cat("\nComputing the CI\n")
  quantile_mat <- apply(coef_mat, 2, function(x){
    stats::quantile(x, probs = c(alpha/2, 1-alpha/2))
  })
  colnames(quantile_mat) <- c("(Intercept)", colnames(X))
  
  return(quantile_mat)
}
  • Let’s use it
ctl <- c(4.17,5.58,5.18,6.11,4.50,4.61,5.17,4.53,5.33,5.14)
trt <- c(4.81,4.17,4.41,3.59,5.87,3.83,6.03,4.89,4.32,4.69)
group <- matrix(c(rep(0, 10), rep(1, 10)), ncol = 1)
colnames(group) <- "group"

weight <-  c(ctl, trt)

res <- bootstrap_lm(X = group,
                    y = weight,
                    verbose = 1)
## [1] "Starting bootstrap"
## **********
## Computing the CI
res
##       (Intercept)      group
## 2.5%     4.678393 -0.8992083
## 97.5%    5.392869  0.2576288

tryCatch(): outputting even when the code crashes

  • Sometimes you’re using someone else’s function many, many times, and that function sometimes unexpectedly crashes given specific inputs. Uh oh!
  • Sad day for you. Unfortunately, you can’t control how other coders behave.
  • What should you do?

The “unlucky” universe: If their function rarely works for most inputs, you’re probably out of luck – you don’t have many great options

  • Option 1 (Re-implement): Since R is open-source, you can look at their implementation, copy-paste their implementation into your R package (of course, citing their work!), and manually fixing their code. This way, you don’t need to start from ground-zero, but this will still realistically be a lot of work. Do-able, but painful.
  • Option 2 (Search elsewhere): To look online at other implementations of the same or similar problems. Maybe someone else coded a different function that works. (This is why as you code more, you’ll become more and more used to reading other people’s code. This is also where your colleagues and advisors might have some suggestions.)
  • Option 3 (Consider alternative paths): You might need change your entire strategy on how to solve your problem. (This is actually the most common route you’ll pick.) There are many paths to solve a problem, and unfortunately, the path you set out was more thorny than you had realized.

The “not great, but not that bad” universe: If their function works as intended for most inputs, you can still use their function as long as you’re somewhat clever.

  • Option 1 (Thorough understanding): If you somehow spent time to figure out why the function sometimes unexpectedly crashes (typically in a “corner case”), then you can simply avoid calling the function in this special settings.
# (This is fictitious pseudo-code)
my_function <- function(input){
  # check if the input is a corner case for someone_elses_function()
  if(check_argument(input)){
    
    # my custom code to handle this corner case
  } else {
    
    # otherwise, use someone_elses_function()
    someone_elses_function(input)
  }
}
  • Option 2 (TryCatch): You can “wrap” their function in a tryCatch(), whereby you write code that executes specifically when their function errors. (This is a common route to pick since this doesn’t require you completely understand why their function crashed. However, the tradeoff is that this means you’ll always be trying to use their function regardless of if the inputs are appropriate, which might make the overall function slower. If you can pick Option 1, I’ll always encourage choosing Option 1 over Option 2.)
# (This is fictitious pseudo-code)
my_function <- function(input){
  tryCatch(someone_elses_function(input),
           error = function(e){
             # do something else with input
           })
}

Examples of tryCatch() in action

I’ll give two examples of how to use tryCatch().

The typical workflow of a tryCatch() function is:

tryCatch(
  {
    ## Write code here that you hope to use
    ## If this is ONE function call (i.e., NOT a many lines of code)
    ## then you don't need the {}'s.
    ## However, you'll still need the comma at the end
  },
  error = function(e){
    # Write code here on what to do in case the first 
    # code block crashed
  }
)

(It’s a longer discussion that I won’t get to on why you’re writing error=function(e){}. This has to do with signals and conditions in R.)

Example 1: Error when using K-means clustering

  • K-means clustering clusters a bunch of rows of a matrix in a “meaningful” way. (You will learn this in some machine learning class in the future, if you haven’t already)

  • The stats::kmeans() function usually works pretty well for this.

set.seed(0)
mat_list <- lapply(1:2, function(k){
  MASS::mvrnorm(n = 100, 
                mu = rep(k*5, 2), 
                Sigma = diag(2))
})
mat <- do.call(rbind, mat_list)
plot(mat[,1], 
     mat[,2],
     asp = TRUE,
     pch = 16,
     xlab = "Dimension 1",
     ylab = "Dimension 2")

kmeans_res <- stats::kmeans(mat, 
                            centers = 2)
plot(mat[,1], 
     mat[,2],
     asp = TRUE,
     pch = 16,
     col = kmeans_res$cluster+1,
     xlab = "Dimension 1",
     ylab = "Dimension 2")

  • However, the stats::kmeans() function is known to crash when there are more cluster centers requested than distinct data points.
mat_constant <- cbind(rep(1, 10),
                      rep(2, 10))
# each row of mat_constant is exactly c(1,2)
mat_constant
##       [,1] [,2]
##  [1,]    1    2
##  [2,]    1    2
##  [3,]    1    2
##  [4,]    1    2
##  [5,]    1    2
##  [6,]    1    2
##  [7,]    1    2
##  [8,]    1    2
##  [9,]    1    2
## [10,]    1    2
kmeans_res <- stats::kmeans(mat_constant, 
                            centers = 2)
## Error in stats::kmeans(mat_constant, centers = 2): more cluster centers than distinct data points.
  • If you’re using this function many many times on different datasets, you might not realize some datasets are “degenerate” in this sense
  • For those of you doing research: Specifically for clustering, this is a very common encountered error when you’re developing a sub-sampling procedure for clustering (either sub-sampling rows or columns of a matrix, and then doing the clustering)
  • To get around this, you might add a random amount of “jitter” to the data only if stats::kmeans() crashes.
kmeans_safe <- function(mat, centers){
  tryCatch(
    stats::kmeans(mat, 
                  centers = centers),
    error = function(e){
      mat_tmp <- apply(mat, 2, function(x){
        n <- length(x)
        sd_val <- stats::sd(x)
        if(sd_val == 0) sd_val <- 0.01
        x_new <- x + stats::rnorm(n, 
                                  mean = 0,
                                  sd = sd_val/10)
        
        return(x_new)
      })
      
      stats::kmeans(mat_tmp, 
                    centers = centers)
    }
  )
}

kmeans_res <- kmeans_safe(mat_constant, 
                          centers = 2)
kmeans_res$cluster
##  [1] 2 2 1 1 1 1 1 1 2 2

Example 2: Error when computing the inverse of a matrix

  • Suppose I’m computing the inverse of a matrix via solve(). This works most of the time as intended.
mat1
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    2    1    1
## [2,]    1    2    0
## [3,]    1    0    2
inverse1 <- solve(mat1)
inverse1
##      [,1]  [,2]  [,3]
## [1,]  1.0 -0.50 -0.50
## [2,] -0.5  0.75  0.25
## [3,] -0.5  0.25  0.75
# it's indeed the inverse!
inverse1 %*% mat1
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    0    0
## [2,]    0    1    0
## [3,]    0    0    1
mat1 %*% inverse1
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    0    0
## [2,]    0    1    0
## [3,]    0    0    1
  • However, what happens if the matrix isn’t invertible? This scenario might accidentally happen because I’m computing the inverse of many many matrices (for example, many different datasets), and sometimes, unbeknowst to me, some matrices are not invertible.
mat2
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    5    2   -3
## [2,]    2    1   -2
## [3,]   -3   -2    5
inverse2 <- solve(mat2)
## Error in solve.default(mat2): Lapack routine dgesv: system is exactly singular: U[3,3] = 0
# uh oh!
  • I might want write a custom function that does error handling via tryCatch() to more gracefully handle this scenario.
  • We’re going to exploit a mathematical trick: If a symmetric matrix is non-invertible, then adding any small constant along the diagonal will always result in an invertible matrix. (This is something you can prove to yourself using the eigendecomposition)
solve_safe <- function(mat){
  tryCatch(
    solve(mat),
    error = function(e){
      n <- nrow(mat)
      tmp <- mat + 0.01*diag(n)
      solve(tmp)
    }
  )
}

inverse2 <- solve_safe(mat2)
inverse2
##            [,1]      [,2]      [,3]
## [1,]   5.853640 -22.19756 -5.356127
## [2,] -22.197558  88.90122 22.197558
## [3,]  -5.356127  22.19756  5.853640
# Of course, since mat2 wasn't originally invertible,
# this means inverse2 isn't a "true" inverse of mat2.
# However, at least our code didn't crash, and this might
# be okay depending on what we were doing with inverse2.
inverse2 %*% mat2
##            [,1]       [,2]        [,3]
## [1,] 0.94146360  0.2219756  0.05356127
## [2,] 0.22197558  0.1109878 -0.22197558
## [3,] 0.05356127 -0.2219756  0.94146360
  • Note: This example is a bit more pathological than Example 2. I wouldn’t really recommending doing this example in practice, but it’s mainly to illustrate tryCatch().

A few notes:

  • While I framed someone else’s code crashing as “that person coded the function poorly”, I’m exaggerating
  • Different authors have different understanding of what is a “sensible” design
  • For a “corner case”, one author might think it’s a good thing that function crashes, since they might deem it nonsensical to calculate the output for such a degenerate setting.
  • Another author might think it’s a bad thing for the function thing to crash, since they might deem it important for the function to always output something regardless of how nonsensical the input is.
  • As you code more and more, you’ll realize there are more opinions in software engineering than you probably currently realize

A few more notes about tryCatch

  • tryCatch() actually is a lot more complex than I’m telling you
  • While the most common usage of tryCatch() is to handle errors (i.e., the function you’re using inside your function crashes – 90%+ of the time you’re using a tryCatch() is specifically for this scenario), two other relatively common usages of tryCatch() to handle warnings as well as an appending a finally flag.
  • These are a bit nuanced, so I’m not going to talk about them
  • However, you can read the documentation of tryCatch(), and there will links to optional reading material at the end of these slides that you can use
  • In my experience, 99% of your coding experience, you don’t need to use tryCatch(), but for those remaining 1%, your understanding of how tryCatch() will really shine
  • However, for your upcoming HW4, you’ll be using tryCatch() a lot since you’re about to use everyone else’s maximal partial clique functions…

“My code is slow.” Now what?

Onto the second half of the lecture.

  • Let’s say you’ve coded your function but it’s slow.
  • You’re frustrated, and you’re convinced you know how to make it faster.
  • What should you do?

Once again, being a “good coder” is only partially about writing “code that works.” Here, the theme is that instead of arbitrarily picking a part of your complex function that you’re going to improve, you should take an evidence-based approach

  • Do you even know which part of your code is slow? What evidence do you have for your suspicions?

Basics of timing your code

Before we get into into “profiling” your code, let’s discuss how to time your code.

  • This is most commonly used simply using the system.time() function.
set.seed(0)
n <- 500
mat <- matrix(stats::rnorm(n^2), 
              nrow = n,
              ncol = n)
system.time(svd(mat))
##    user  system elapsed 
##   0.259   0.001   0.261
  • The elapsed column is how much “real” time has passed. (This is usually the number you care about.)
  • This is the sum of the user time (i.e., how much time your code spent running) and system time (i.e., how much time your operation system spent preparing to run your code)
  • Unless you’re working with datasets that cannot be stored in RAM (i.e., large datasets) or parallelized methods, the system time is usually neglible.
  • Another way to time your functions is to use Sys.time(), which returns the clock time on your computer.
  • This is useful if you have a print() statement in your function that outputs the current status of your function (i.e., a verbose argument)
set.seed(0)
n <- 500
mat <- matrix(stats::rnorm(n^2), 
              nrow = n,
              ncol = n)

# start your timer
time_start <- Sys.time()

res <- svd(mat)
# you can include other lines of code here

# end your timer
time_end <- Sys.time()

time_start
## [1] "2025-05-15 07:39:49 PDT"
time_end-time_start
## Time difference of 0.2656319 secs

Using the microbenchmark package

  • What if you’re worried that the things going on in your computer might affect the timing, or that the order of which functions you test might affect your results?
  • These concerns happen most commonly when you’re doing a head-to-head comparison between two implements that take in the same inputs and outputs
  • We’ll come back to this after my demo in the next slide!

Example: Coding linear regression by hand

  • We’re now going to talk about profiling your code
  • To do this, I need a function to profile
  • Below, I’m going to code my own linear-regression solver, which uses the closed-form solution of linear regression that I’m sure you all already learned
  • (This is an example. In general, I would not recommend coding your own linear regression function, and instead just use the stats::lm() function. stats::lm() has a lot of very useful engineering behind it that makes it likely a lot more stable than most implementations you would make yourself.)
lm_custom <- function(X, y){
  stopifnot(is.matrix(X),
            !is.matrix(y),
            is.numeric(X),
            is.numeric(y),
            nrow(X) == length(y))
  
  n <- nrow(X)
  
  # append the intercept term
  X <- cbind(1, X)
  colnames(X)[1] <- "(Intercept)"
  
  # compute the inverse of X's covariance
  cross_mat <- t(X) %*% X
  inv_mat <- solve(cross_mat)
  
  inner_prod <- t(X) %*% y
  
  beta_vec <- as.numeric(inv_mat %*% inner_prod)
  
  # put the column names on
  names(beta_vec) <- colnames(X)
  return(beta_vec)
}
  • Let’s use this implementation, and convince ourselves its correct by comparing against stats::lm(). (This could be a unit test if this were in an R package!)
ctl <- c(4.17,5.58,5.18,6.11,4.50,4.61,5.17,4.53,5.33,5.14)
trt <- c(4.81,4.17,4.41,3.59,5.87,3.83,6.03,4.89,4.32,4.69)
group <- matrix(c(rep(0, 10), rep(1, 10)), ncol = 1)
colnames(group) <- "group"
weight <- c(ctl, trt)

# this is the usual way
lm_res <- stats::lm(weight ~ group)
beta_vec1 <- stats::coef(lm_res)
beta_vec1
## (Intercept)       group 
##       5.032      -0.371
# this is our way
beta_vec2 <- lm_custom(X = group,
                       y = weight)
beta_vec2
## (Intercept)       group 
##       5.032      -0.371

Here is the implementation of lm_custom() again:

            !is.matrix(y),

            is.numeric(y),

  • Pause.
  • Take a guess which part of lm_custom() takes the most time.
  • Let’s hear some guesses.
  • Now let’s profile our code. This is done via the Rprof() function
  • You need to turn on and off the Rprof(), since, when you turn Rprof() on, it’s recording (in very fast intervals) everything going on in your function.
  • Since you’re profile code, we need a function that takes more than a couple seconds to complete (in order to get meaningful results)
  • One option to simply repeat a calculation many many times
set.seed(0)
n <- 100
d <- 20
X <- matrix(stats::rnorm(d*n),
            ncol = d,
            nrow = n)
colnames(X) <- paste0("var", 1:d)

  • The sample.interval is how often the R profiler (in terms of seconds) checking what function is currently being executed

  • The sampling.time is the total elapsed time that the profiler was on for

  • The $self.pct and $total.pct outputs are two different ways to tabulate time. (pct stands for “percent”. The self.pct times will always add up to 100% by definition.)

  • $total.pct adds counts the elapsed time for a function to include the elapsed time for any of the helper function that it itself calls. (That is, if function A() uses function B() inside it, whenever the sampler is inside B(), it counts towards the time spent in A())

  • $self.pct only counts the time each function call is used. (That is, if function A() uses function B() inside it, whenever the sampler is inside B(), it does not count towards the time in A())

  • If you look at t.default under $by.total, you’ll see more than 40% of the time, the lm_custom() was simply transposing a matrix!
  • If you wanted to wanted to know how to get most “bang for your buck” when optimizing your code, this is a very good clue. If you made the t() function faster (or avoided it entirely), you could speed up your function a lot!
  • Let’s just give an example of what your function might look like after you optimized it. Here, I avoid using the t() function and instead directly use crossprod() or tcrossprod().
lm_custom_v2 <- function(X, y){
  stopifnot(is.matrix(X),
            !is.matrix(y),
            is.numeric(X),
            is.numeric(y),
            nrow(X) == length(y))
  
  n <- nrow(X)
  
  # append the intercept term
  X <- cbind(1, X)
  colnames(X)[1] <- "(Intercept)"
  
  # compute the inverse of X's covariance
  cross_mat <- crossprod(X)
  inv_mat <- solve(cross_mat)
  
  inner_prod <- crossprod(X, y)
  
  beta_vec <- as.numeric(inv_mat %*% inner_prod)
  
  # put the column names on
  names(beta_vec) <- colnames(X)
  return(beta_vec)
}
  • Let’s make sure our implementation still gives the correct answer
# this is our way
beta_vec2 <- lm_custom_v2(X = group,
                          y = weight)

##       5.032      -0.371

  • Notice now, crossprod() doesn’t even take that much time! (Aside: This is because crossprod(X) implements a way to essentially do t(X)%*%X without ever actually calling the t() function.)
  • Now, we can see the solve() function is the bottleneck in terms of time
  • Hence, (if this were a more complex function), we’ll know the next suspect on how to improve the performance of our code

Back to microbenchmark

The microbenchmark package gives you a simple way to test similar functions many, many times and record the timings, via the microbenchmark::microbenchmark() function.

# example from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42773206/when-is-crossprod-preferred-to-and-when-isnt
library(microbenchmark)
## Warning: package 'microbenchmark' was built under R version 4.3.3
set.seed(0)
A <- matrix(runif(2000 * 2000), 2000)
x <- runif(2000)

result <- microbenchmark::microbenchmark(t = {t(A) %*% x}, 
                                         crossprod = {crossprod(A, x)},
                                         times = 1000)
## Warning in microbenchmark::microbenchmark(t = {: less accurate nanosecond times
## to avoid potential integer overflows
result
## Unit: milliseconds
##       expr      min       lq     mean   median        uq       max neval
##          t 7.169916 7.766835 9.614242 9.922779 10.980169 44.591600  1000
##  crossprod 5.470220 5.544492 5.648758 5.625262  5.723415  6.283209  1000

You can actually plot the results since they have their own class

class(result)
## [1] "microbenchmark" "data.frame"
plot(result)

Takeaway: Profile your code before you start optimizing your code

  • Profiling your code isn’t something happens inside your R package
  • Instead, it’s something you do after you’ve written your function in your R package, find it suspiciously slow when you’re using it, and you fidget with it in the R console
